VALUE of fish sold in registered markets rose by 47.6 per cent to 136.8bn/- in the fourth quarter of last year from the value recorded in the corresponding quarter of the 2020 due to increase in both price and volume. According to the Bank of Tanzania (BoT) Consolidated Zonal Economic Performance Report for the quarter ending December last year all zones recorded increase in value except the Central zone. Lake Zone accounted for 57.4 per cent of the total value, trailed by South Eastern zone (17.5 per cent). The Lake zone registered 7,491.7 tonnes of fish worth 78.5bn/- in the quarter ending December last year compared to 6,629.9 tonnes valued 48.6bn/- in the corresponding period a year before, representing 13 per cent increase. In the South Eastern zone, a total of 5,425.1 tonnes of fish recorded valued 23.9bn/- compared to 5,468.7 tonnes of fish in the corresponding period a year before 17.6bn/-, equivalent to 35.9 per cent rise. During the period under review, a total of 4,164 tonnes of fish was recorded in Southern Highlands zone worth 15.1bn/- compared to 2,697.3 tonnes of fish in the other quarter in 2020, representing 12.2bn/-, representing 24.5 per cent change. In the Dar es Salaam zone, a total of 3,530.4 tonnes of fish were registered in period under review worth 11.5bn/- compared to 2,845.8 tonnes of fish in the corresponding period valued 8.4bn/- which is equivalent to 37 per cent change. In the reference period, a total of 1,852 tonnes were registered in the northern zone worth 7.4bn/- compared to 1,583.7 tonnes in the corresponding period valued 5.2bn/- in the corresponding quarter, representing 43.5 per cent change. In the central zone, a total of 59.1 tonnes were registered in the reference quarter valued 302.1m/- compared to 161.1 tonnes recorded in the corresponding period worth 750.9m/-, equivalent to negative 59.8 per cent change.